Module 4: Data Exploration

Data Exploration

The primary task before analysis is exploring our data. This allows us to evaulate the appropriateness of statistical procedures, the linearity of relationships and explore how missing data may affect our results. In this module we will discover some of the tools available in R for data exploration.

Missingness

Missing data points in R are represented by NA. The function is.na()` is an extrememly useful way of idenitfiying missing values. is.na() will return TRUE for missing values and FALSE for non-missing values.

x <- c(2, 4, NA, 10, 11, NA, 3)
is.na(x)
## [1] FALSE FALSE  TRUE FALSE FALSE  TRUE FALSE
# remember that we can select values where a function is equal to true using
# subsetting
x[is.na(x)]
## [1] NA NA
x[!is.na(x)]
## [1]  2  4 10 11  3

A side note about NAs and subsetting Subsetting with NA will always return NA. For example:

x
## [1]  2  4 NA 10 11 NA  3
# here the equality NA < 5 returns NA so where NA is in x this returns NA
x[x < 5] 
## [1]  2  4 NA NA  3
# what do you think this will return?
x < 5
# run it and find out - were you right?

Some functions functions will return NA if any NAs are present in their arguments. Examples include sum, mean, range, min, max, quantiles. This behaviour can be changed with the argument na.rm = T

sum(x)
## [1] NA
sum(x, na.rm = T)
## [1] 30
range(x)
## [1] NA NA
range(x, na.rm = T)
## [1]  2 11

Read the help for any() and think about what you think the following code will return.

any(x < 0)
any(x < 5)

Now run the code. Was the result what you expected?

We can also explore missingness in categorical variables. Add the useNA = ifany or useNA = always argument to the table function to display missing values.

# to run these examples you will need to download the smokingdata from CANVAS
# and place it a folder titled data in your working directory
load('Data/SmokingData.rda')
table(SmokingData$Gender, SmokingData$Smoker)
##         
##          Current Smoker Former Smoker Never Smoker
##   Female            464           683         1294
##   Male              563           772          931
table(SmokingData$Gender, SmokingData$Smoker, useNA = 'ifany')
##         
##          Current Smoker Former Smoker Never Smoker <NA>
##   Female            464           683         1294   82
##   Male              563           772          931  211
table(SmokingData$Gender, SmokingData$Smoker, useNA = 'always')
##         
##          Current Smoker Former Smoker Never Smoker <NA>
##   Female            464           683         1294   82
##   Male              563           772          931  211
##   <NA>                0             0            0    0

What do you notice about the missing data?

We can also use addNA() and na.omit() to deal with missing data. By using addNA in our table function we can look at missing data for only one of our variables.

table(SmokingData$Smoker, SmokingData$Education)
##                 
##                  High School College Graduate School
##   Current Smoker         391     383             187
##   Former Smoker          573     537             278
##   Never Smoker           210    1236             653
table(SmokingData$Smoker, SmokingData$Education, useNA = 'ifany')
##                 
##                  High School College Graduate School <NA>
##   Current Smoker         391     383             187   66
##   Former Smoker          573     537             278   67
##   Never Smoker           210    1236             653  126
##   <NA>                    78     126              68   21
table(SmokingData$Smoker, addNA(SmokingData$Education))
##                 
##                  High School College Graduate School <NA>
##   Current Smoker         391     383             187   66
##   Former Smoker          573     537             278   67
##   Never Smoker           210    1236             653  126

addNA() adds a level for missing data to a factor.

x <- addNA(SmokingData$Education)
str(x)
##  Factor w/ 4 levels "High School",..: 3 2 2 1 2 2 1 1 2 1 ...
levels(x)
## [1] "High School"     "College"         "Graduate School" NA
head(x, 20)
##  [1] Graduate School College         College         High School    
##  [5] College         College         High School     High School    
##  [9] College         High School     <NA>            High School    
## [13] High School     College         College         High School    
## [17] College         <NA>            High School     College        
## Levels: High School College Graduate School <NA>

na.omit() allows us to select only complete cases. This will remove any observations is a data frame where any of the variables is missing.

summary(SmokingData)
##     Gender                Smoker               Education   
##  Female:2523   Current Smoker:1027   High School    :1252  
##  Male  :2477   Former Smoker :1455   College        :2282  
##                Never Smoker  :2225   Graduate School:1186  
##                NA's          : 293   NA's           : 280
completecases <- na.omit(SmokingData)
summary(completecases)
##     Gender                Smoker               Education   
##  Female:2317   Current Smoker: 961   High School    :1174  
##  Male  :2131   Former Smoker :1388   College        :2156  
##                Never Smoker  :2099   Graduate School:1118

Plots

R has a number of base plotting options and because we use code to create them, they are reproducible and change with the data!

# cars is a built in R data set with speed and dist (it is included with the
# install - you don't need to do anything to use it) for more info:
?cars

First just a basic plot of speed v distance

plot(cars)

A nice overview of the data, but lets spice it up a little.

plot(cars, 
     pch = 4, # sets the type of point - here will use a cross
     col = 'purple', # set the color - 
     # r will accept a wide variety of colour names as well as hexidecimal 
     # equivalents
     main = 'Speed vs Stopping Distance in the Cars data', # set the main title
     xlab = 'Speed (mph)', # set the x axis title
     ylab = 'Stopping Distance (ft)' # set the y axis title
     )

A complete list of available symbols](https://www.statmethods.net/advgraphs/parameters.html)

Now, lets add a regression line.

plot(cars, 
     pch = 16, # let's the change the point to a filled circle
     col = '#0000cc', # set the color - 
     main = 'Speed vs Stopping Distance in the Cars data', # set the main title
     xlab = 'Speed (mph)', # set the x axis title
     ylab = 'Stopping Distance (ft)' # set the y axis title
     )
abline(lm(dist ~ speed, data = cars))

mtcars$cyl <- factor(mtcars$cyl, levels = c(4, 6, 8), 
                     labels = c('Four Cylinder', 
                                'Six Cylinder', 
                                'Eight Cylinder'))
mtcars$vs <- factor(mtcars$vs, levels = 0:1, 
                    labels = c('V-shaped', 'straight'))
mtcars$am <- factor(mtcars$am, levels = 0:1, 
                    labels = c('automatic', 'manual'))

R will often guess the type of plot we want based on the data that was passed to it. For example in the plots above R guessed we wanted the first variable in cars plotted against the second variable in cars and because they were both continuous - it gave us a scatter plot.

plot(mtcars$cyl)

plot(mtcars$hp)

plot(mtcars$hp ~ mtcars$cyl)

plot(mtcars$cyl ~ mtcars$hp)

Does it appear there is a relationship between horse power and number of cylinders?

plot(mtcars$am ~ mtcars$cyl)

plot(mtcars$hp ~ mtcars$wt)

Do you think theres an association between transmission type and number of cylinders? How about between horse power and weight?

Lets look at a histogram of miles per gallon.

hist(mtcars$mpg, 
     col = '#33cc33', 
     main = 'Histogram of Miles per Gallon', 
     xlab = 'MPG')

Use ?hist, ?plot, and ?par to explore further graphing options. For further study check out Quick-R: Graphs and Quick-R: Advanced Graphs.

Saving Graphs

The easist way to save graphs is to use the export button on the plot viewer in Rstudio.
